    "decision_handoff_body": "\n# Decision summary\n\nFresh synthesis-stage verification after the window closed strongly supports Yes. The governing XTracker surface still maps to the correct verified Trump account, the exact April 3-April 10 tracking object is now inactive, and a fresh exact-window query returns 108 in-window posts, which is comfortably inside the 100-119 band. The pre-close disagreement across personas was mostly about live overshoot risk; that timing risk has now resolved in favor of Yes.\n\n## Why this may matter now\n\nMarket-implied probability was 0.81. My final syndicated range is 0.95 to 0.99. The edge now looks actionable on the Yes side because fresh synthesis-stage verification after the window closed shows 108 exact-window posts on XTracker, comfortably inside 100-119. The prior market may have been mispriced because earlier evidence was pre-close and still exposed to overshoot risk, while the fresh post-close check largely removes that risk.\n\n## Shift versus swarm baseline\n\nThis is materially above the swarm-implied center because the synthesis has fresher evidence than the swarm did. The raw personas were mostly working from a 103 snapshot while the window was still open, so their discounts for overshoot risk were reasonable at the time. The synthesis-stage refresh now shows 108 after the relevant window closed, resolving the main prior uncertainty in favor of Yes.\n\n## Edge verification status\n\nVerification quality is high. I independently re-checked the XTracker user endpoint, confirming the correct verified Trump account; re-checked the active/inactive tracking status, confirming the exact April 3-April 10 tracking is now inactive; and ran a fresh exact-window posts query through the full endDate of 2026-04-10T15:59:59.000Z, which returned 108 posts. What remains unverified at the highest level is item-by-item labeling of why each record is counted under contract rules, but with 108 comfortably in-range that gap is less likely to alter the directional conclusion.\n\n## Compression toward market\n\nNo. Earlier caution and compression were warranted while the market was live. Fresh verification strengthened rather than weakened the edge because it removed the main unresolved tail: a late burst above 119 before noon ET.\n\n## Timing and catalyst posture\n\nThe key catalyst has already passed: the market window closed. The main remaining checkpoint is official market settlement or any correction notice. The edge is more likely to decay than widen from here because most of the informational advantage came from refreshing the governing source after close but before full downstream repricing or settlement.\n\n## Key blockers\n\nThere are no major decision blockers left. The only meaningful residual blocker is that the public API still does not fully expose per-item inclusion/exclusion labels, so a tiny settlement-mechanics tail remains. That is not large enough to block a high-confidence Yes handoff.\n\n## Best countercase\n\nThe best remaining countercase is the risk-manager / variant-view style concern that the public exact-window posts result may not be identical to the official counted counter if some records are later excluded under reply/main-feed or similar mechanics. But to flip the answer, such a discrepancy would have to move the final official number from 108 to outside 100-119, which is now a much weaker countercase.\n\n## What would change the view\n\nAn official correction, settlement notice, or stronger source showing that the official counted counter for the closed window differs materially from the refreshed exact-window result would reduce confidence. To truly change the directional view, that discrepancy would likely need to push the official total below 100 or above 119.\n\n## Recommended next action\n\nNo follow-up needed for the forecast itself. Hand off as strong Yes and optionally monitor only for official settlement or any correction notice.\n\n## Verification impact\n\nYes, synthesis-stage verification materially changed the conclusion. The new pass refreshed the governing source after close and showed 108 exact-window posts, replacing pre-close uncertainty with post-close evidence. Cross-lane comparison shows the main lane disagreement was not really about core facts or contract hierarchy; it was about how much to discount a still-live overshoot tail. That discrepancy now mostly collapses.\n",
